00:07:53.970 --> 00:07:58.270
and I think that's worth
exploring a little bit.

00:07:58.270 --> 00:08:00.680
What makes a good band leader?

00:08:00.680 --> 00:08:01.980
&gt;&gt; Jayme Stone: That's
a good question.

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:03.620
I've done it for a longtime.

00:08:03.620 --> 00:08:08.020 position:56%
I think, you know, I started playing
banjo 22 years ago and very soon

00:08:08.020 --> 00:08:11.790
after knew that I wanted
to play the banjo in a way

00:08:11.790 --> 00:08:16.270
that didn't particularly exist,
and I wanted to make music

00:08:16.270 --> 00:08:21.960
that combined things that were you
know not typically found together.

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:25.270
So, it was clear that I
wasn't going to get a call.

00:08:25.270 --> 00:08:27.920
Like no one was going to say,
you know, come play bowed banjo

00:08:27.920 --> 00:08:32.580
on my record or you know we
have this idea for a project

00:08:32.580 --> 00:08:34.390
of West African music or, you know,

00:08:34.390 --> 00:08:36.810
we want a chambers
symphony with banjo.

00:08:36.810 --> 00:08:38.840
You know, so if I was
going to do the things

00:08:38.840 --> 00:08:42.670
that you know were lighting up in
head I would have to create it.

00:08:42.670 --> 00:08:46.540
And so I had been thinking for
a longtime how to cultivate

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:51.630
and create a context you know for
the things that I wanted to do

00:08:51.630 --> 00:08:54.990
and that really involves
people and working with people,

00:08:54.990 --> 00:08:57.290
and I love collaborating.

00:08:57.290 --> 00:09:00.840
And, you know, what comes
to mind is actually a,

00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:05.570
there's a beautiful movie
that Wim Wenders made

00:09:05.570 --> 00:09:08.240
about Pina Bausch;
have you seen this?

00:09:08.240 --> 00:09:13.050
She's an amazing choreographer and
she worked with the same company,

00:09:13.050 --> 00:09:15.350
of course, people came in that,
but for many, many, many years

00:09:15.350 --> 00:09:21.550
and she had this process where
she would essentially present

00:09:21.550 --> 00:09:23.800
like prompts.

00:09:23.800 --> 00:09:26.440 position:56%
You know, she would say like you
know what does it, what does it look

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:30.940
like in your arms to you know be
a cactus or something like that?

00:09:30.940 --> 00:09:32.940
Or things you know
related to whatever;

00:09:32.940 --> 00:09:36.210
theme that she was beginning to
cultivate for a certain piece

00:09:36.210 --> 00:09:42.310
of choreography and they
would move how, you know,

00:09:42.310 --> 00:09:46.100
they felt like naturally
you know from that

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:49.640
and then she would make notes
or later photograph and film

00:09:49.640 --> 00:09:54.250
and she would curate you know
their own personal language

00:09:54.250 --> 00:09:57.450 position:56%
and she had the big umbrella vision.

00:09:57.450 --> 00:09:58.750
You know, and she was
the choreographer

00:09:58.750 --> 00:10:02.040
but she really used their
voices or their bodies in a way.

00:10:02.040 --> 00:10:05.710
And I remember being really
moved when I saw that film,

00:10:05.710 --> 00:10:08.330
because it was something
I'd been trying to do

00:10:08.330 --> 00:10:11.430
but maybe a little bit shyly
because I felt like, you know,

00:10:11.430 --> 00:10:13.490
maybe I needed to be more
of a capital C composer

00:10:13.490 --> 00:10:17.260 position:56%
and you know write out all the parts
and you know and I've done some

00:10:17.260 --> 00:10:20.530
of that, but what I find most
satisfying is to really find people

00:10:20.530 --> 00:10:26.130
that have a singular way of
playing and that I resonate with

00:10:26.130 --> 00:10:30.950
and create a process by which
they can really be themselves

00:10:30.950 --> 00:10:33.370
and then I can kind of
go back in and figure

00:10:33.370 --> 00:10:35.730
out like what works
together and shape it,

00:10:35.730 --> 00:10:38.650
so I think of myself almost
as the curator of the music

00:10:38.650 --> 00:10:41.750
or the arrangements
rather than sort of coming

00:10:41.750 --> 00:10:44.090
in with a big monolithic decision.

00:10:44.090 --> 00:10:46.490
&gt;&gt; Todd Harvey: So that
must necessitate a lot

00:10:46.490 --> 00:10:50.540
of rehearsal time upfront,
is that true?

00:10:50.540 --> 00:10:51.840
&gt;&gt; Jayme Stone: That's true.

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:56.340 position:56%
I've also been working with people
I've known for a while, so you know,

00:10:56.340 --> 00:11:01.650
you know musicians who are
steeped in all the things

00:11:01.650 --> 00:11:05.460
that these musicians are you
know where they're improvisers

00:11:05.460 --> 00:11:09.730
and they know traditional music and
they; we share a lot of references.

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:12.660
You know, I can say like oh yeah
you know we want this thing that's

00:11:12.660 --> 00:11:15.080
like a Bobby McFerrin
circle song, you know.

00:11:15.080 --> 00:11:18.890
And that can be like right, you
know, and when you work with people

00:11:18.890 --> 00:11:22.490
that are cut from the same cloth or
you know you have a history with,

00:11:22.490 --> 00:11:26.640
there's this shared language
and you'd be astonished

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:32.050
at how quick the process can be you
know with really great musicians.

00:11:32.050 --> 00:11:35.100
And then there's the secondary
process where you then hone

00:11:35.100 --> 00:11:36.740
and you know things get seasoned,

00:11:36.740 --> 00:11:42.380
but a lot of times you know I've
become a bigger believer in like a,

00:11:42.380 --> 00:11:44.720
you know, first thought/best
thought sometimes.

00:11:44.720 --> 00:11:47.220
You know, like that arrangement
of "Old Paint" kind of came to,

00:11:47.220 --> 00:11:50.060
it was the first thing that
we ever did with Tim O'Brien,

00:11:50.060 --> 00:11:52.940
and Moira Smiley, and Margaret
Glaspy, and Greg Garrison.

00:11:52.940 --> 00:11:57.130
And Margaret had brought in,

00:11:57.130 --> 00:11:59.940
well actually there's this
really curious Lomax recording

00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:05.760
where he's interviewing Vera Hall,
you know, from Livingston, Alabama

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:08.800
and he actually start, she
was such an phenomenal singer

00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:11.440
that he started testing her to see

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:14.860
if she could back whatever
melodies you know he played her

00:12:14.860 --> 00:12:16.160
or sang to her.

00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:19.960
And so he actually played her a
recording of "Goodbye Old Paint"

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:24.080 position:56%
which was not in repertoire, not a
song she did and she hummed it back,

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:29.070
you know and of course, like all
you know amazing musicians couldn't

00:12:29.070 --> 00:12:31.440
help, but you know it
came out sounding like her

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:33.730
and it was actually that,

00:12:33.730 --> 00:12:37.390
that little snippet for
25 seconds no words.

00:12:37.390 --> 00:12:42.000
She just hummed the melody that
Margaret Glaspy used to kind

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.750 position:56%
of rework the verse; she brought
that in and it just sort of happened

00:12:45.750 --> 00:12:49.950 position:56%
and around you know, I said well you
know, we can't leave out the chorus

00:12:49.950 --> 00:12:52.560
in the whole part of the story
