00:43:55.010 --> 00:43:56.310
down and wait for it to come up,

00:43:56.310 --> 00:43:59.350
so Todd just said let's
just go downstairs.

00:43:59.350 --> 00:44:02.830
So, literally within 5 minutes
of being here for the first time,

00:44:02.830 --> 00:44:07.070
we were walking around with a
shopping cart through the archives.

00:44:07.070 --> 00:44:09.480
Am I allowed to say this out loud?

00:44:09.480 --> 00:44:11.340
&gt;&gt; Todd Harvey: Well, we're not
selling anything just be clear

00:44:11.340 --> 00:44:12.640
about that.

00:44:12.640 --> 00:44:14.560
&gt;&gt; Jayme Stone: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:44:14.560 --> 00:44:18.870
And literally pulling
stuff off of shelves.

00:44:18.870 --> 00:44:22.840
I remember there was like an
odd shaped box that was bigger

00:44:22.840 --> 00:44:25.280
than the rest, so of course
I was interested in it.

00:44:25.280 --> 00:44:26.580
&gt;&gt; Todd Harvey: And I
was like what's that?

00:44:26.580 --> 00:44:28.400
&gt;&gt; Jayme Stone: And I remember you
said, oh yeah you should take that.

00:44:28.400 --> 00:44:31.120
It was all the letters that
Woody Guthrie had ever sent

00:44:31.120 --> 00:44:35.280
to the Lomax family
and then, you know,

00:44:35.280 --> 00:44:41.610
I remember even seeing
the Ampex suitcase model,

00:44:41.610 --> 00:44:43.890
the first stereo recorder
that Lomax had used

00:44:43.890 --> 00:44:47.290
on this whole southern journey
and I, you know, we kind of peered

00:44:47.290 --> 00:44:50.370
in the box and I recognized
it from the picture.

00:44:50.370 --> 00:44:53.830
There's this great picture of him
with Wade Ward where Wade's smiling

00:44:53.830 --> 00:44:57.980
with a few teeth missing, listening
on headphones like probably

00:44:57.980 --> 00:45:00.800
for the first time like hearing
himself being played back

00:45:00.800 --> 00:45:06.320
and you know, yeah like you
talk about physically, you know,

00:45:06.320 --> 00:45:10.460
I am someone that very much
lives in their imagination

00:45:10.460 --> 00:45:14.480
and to be quite honest like a
lot of these characters even

00:45:14.480 --> 00:45:17.460
when I had read the Lomax
biography, you know,

00:45:17.460 --> 00:45:19.300
they were kind of fanciful stories.

00:45:19.300 --> 00:45:23.980
And it actually wasn't until I
was here there in the basement

00:45:23.980 --> 00:45:27.740
where it was like, I remember
holding the first acetate disc

00:45:27.740 --> 00:45:30.090
that Lead Belly ever recorded,

00:45:30.090 --> 00:45:37.580 position:56%
and you know seeing the John Lomax's
beautiful handwriting jotting

00:45:37.580 --> 00:45:41.860
down notes, you know, good
guitar playing and you know notes

00:45:41.860 --> 00:45:45.080
on desk jackets of like who else
in the county they should go visit

00:45:45.080 --> 00:45:49.920
and this kind of thing, and it hit
me like wow these were real people

00:45:49.920 --> 00:45:53.970
that had their lives at this
intersection of, you know,

00:45:53.970 --> 00:45:59.340
whatever was happening for them,
the music, you know, politics,

00:45:59.340 --> 00:46:03.560
race relations, like there were
so many things that were all kind

00:46:03.560 --> 00:46:07.020
of in the air as this
work was getting done

00:46:07.020 --> 00:46:09.370
and everybody was trying
to figure out how to do it,

00:46:09.370 --> 00:46:12.290
how to make a living at it, you
know, and it was so something

00:46:12.290 --> 00:46:15.810
about it like it kind of brought
me down to earth in a lot of ways.

00:46:15.810 --> 00:46:20.700
And the Lomax Project comes with
like 60 pages of liner notes

00:46:20.700 --> 00:46:24.150 position:56%
and photographs, because it became
really important to me to like think

00:46:24.150 --> 00:46:26.050
about where these songs come from

00:46:26.050 --> 00:46:28.880
and how they ended
up where they are.

00:46:28.880 --> 00:46:31.180
Yeah.

